sec.p:
The order of appearance in such unmarked cases is usually right–left, but there are instances when this is not true, as when Abram speaks to Lot or Job expresses his frustration:14
If you go to the left, I’ll go to the right;
if you go to the right, I’ll go to the left. (Gen 13.9)
On the left he hides, and I cannot behold him;
I turn to the right, but I cannot see him. (Job 23.9)

In a few such cases, especially in figurative language, left as well as right gets an almost positive reading:
Long life is in her right hand;
in her left hand are riches and honor. (Prov 3.16)

fn.p:
See also Num 22.26; 1 Kgs 7.21, 39, 49; 22.19; 2 Kgs 11.11; 2 Chr 3.17; 4.6–8; 18.18;
            23.10; Neh 8.4; Ezek 1.10; Zech 4.3, 11. In the deuterocanonicals in Greek, see 1 Macc
            5.46, and in the New Testament, Matt 27.38.
